# 1. Record architecture decisions

**Status:** Accepted — 2026-07-14

## Context

	This is a first software project, built partly to learn to create with AI and intended both as a portfolio piece and as a learning journal. Many design and architecture choices are being made along the way, each with real trade-offs. 

## Decision

	Keep a lightweight decision log in the repository under `docs/adr/`, and adopt the Michael Nygard ADR format (Title, Status, Context, Decision, Consequences) as per Claude's suggestions. One decision per file, numbered sequentially, written in Markdown. New decisions get new files; reversed decisions are marked "Superseded by ADR-XXXX" rather than deleted, so the history of thinking is preserved.

## Consequences

- The "why" behind the app is documented and reviewable — people giving feedback can critique the *reasoning*, not just the surface.
- The act of writing each record forces the reasoning to be made explicit, which tends to sharpen it.
- It is a small ongoing effort; the log is only useful if kept current.
- Records are point-in-time snapshots. When a decision changes, a new ADR supersedes the old one rather than editing history.

*Format popularised by Michael Nygard, "Documenting Architecture Decisions" (2011).*
